My Experiment!

I am testing how music effects my focus. I am running the test using a color pattern game on my phone, called Simon Says. I am terrible at this game and it takes a lot of focus for me to do well. I will be measuring if the beats per minute (BPM) of the songs effect my focus (data collected from an online website). I decided on this study because I like to listen to music while working on my homework, so I wanted to see if different songs gave different results.

Specifically, I am asking whether the BPM of a song has an effect on my focus?

\[H_o: \beta_1 = 0\] \[H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0\] \[\alpha = 0.05\]

For this experiment I will use the mathematical model: \[\underbrace{Y_i}_\text{An individuals Y}=\underbrace{\overbrace{\beta_0}^\text{y-intercept} + \overbrace{\beta_1}^\text{slope} \overbrace{X_i}^\text{An individuals X} \ }_\text{true regression relation}+\overbrace{\epsilon_i}^\text{error term}\quad \text{where}\ \overbrace{\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)}^\text{error term normally distributed}\]

Collecting the data I was very careful to try to randomize the order of BPM so I didn’t get tires and cause a correlation accidentally. I also selected songs with a similar sound, they all have lyrics, and they are all songs I know and like.

Testing!

The following tabs organize four variations of my linear regression. C stands for control, and O stands for outlier.

Yes C, Yes O

SELF.lmC <- lm(Score.SS ~ BPM, data = SELF)

Results!

Well, as we can see, the correlation is really weak at best. Two of the four tests (yes-yes, and yes-no) had significant p-values for the slop and the other two did not. Honestly, I don’t know if it was legal to play with my data the way I did but it provided some interesting insight.

It looks like there is no significance to the BPM of music I listen to but there is a significance to the difference between listening to any music and not listening to music. But maybe the high average in my control testing was a fluke. I can’t really tell om this one test with so many uncontrollable variables and such.

Overall, I’d say either I ran a terrible experiment, that the BPM of the songs I listen to doesn’t have an effect on my focus, or the game I was playing didn’t accurately measure focus.
